snippet.title: Honest Trailers | The Lord of the Rings: The Return of the King
snippet.description:
It’s the Honest Trailer for The Lord of the Rings: The Return of The King! After an extended edition sized sabbatical in the woods, Aragon has been given a return to office notice or else he’ll lose his job as the king of all mankind. While The King makes his return, the hobbits return the ring to sender for a full refund, minus shipping and handling (fingering?). It’s the perfect ending to the perfect trilogy, and then it keeps going for another 15-20 minutes but we don’t want it to be over either.

Voice Narration: Jon Bailey the EPIC VOICE GUY (@epicvoiceguy on all socials)

കല്ലാച്ചിനിന്നും വന്ന വലിയമ്മായി

കച്ചറ കുറ്റിച്ചിറ ചെറിയമ്മായി

snippet.title: "Minnesota" - Marsh Family adaptation of "San Francisco (Be Sure to Wear Some Flowers in Your Hair)"
snippet.description:
We hope the good people of San Francisco won’t mind us adapting this iconic track (about their city in the sixties, in the midst of protests and the counterculture movement) to treat the tragedies in recent days and weeks in Minneapolis. The original song was written by John Phillips (of "The Mamas & the Papas") and first released (sung by Scott McKenzie) in 1967, reaching number one in the UK, Germany, Ireland, and New Zealand charts, though only fourth in the US. We chose it because of its link to protest, its soaring refrains, its simplicity, its earnestness, and its celebration of love and solidarity. In our arrangement we haven’t double tracked the vocals but have added harmonies and mandolin/violin lines.

We hope it serves its aim, which is to express solidarity with the courageous and valiant protesters in Minnesota (and beyond), and to memorialise Renée Good and Alex Pretti, and sing their names across the ocean: two innocent American citizens executed on the streets in appalling scenes that so obviously echo waypoints in the historical march of fascism. Taking on the guns, masks, fear, and falsehoods requires more than flowers and songs. But they are powerful nonetheless, especially if they remind folk of previous generations that navigated trauma, and that you are not alone, and others are being inspired your courage and actions in the face of the winter of our times.

We chose it because of its link to protest, its soaring refrains, its simplicity, its earnestness, and its celebration of love and solidarity. In our arrangement we haven’t double tracked the vocals but have added harmonies and mandolin/violin lines.

We hope it serves its aim, which is to express solidarity with the courageous and valiant protesters in Minnesota (and beyond), and to memorialise Renée Good and Alex Pretti, and sing their names across the ocean: two innocent American citizens executed on the streets in appalling scenes that so obviously echo waypoints in the historical march of fascism. Taking on the guns, masks, fear, and falsehoods requires more than flowers and songs. But they are powerful nonetheless, especially if they remind folk of previous generations that navigated trauma, and that you are not alone, and others are being inspired your courage and actions in the face of the winter of our times.

snippet.title: Boutot - J'ai pas les mots
snippet.description:
Grizzly Records Présente:


🎵 Boutot – J’ai pas les mots (Clip officiel)


Quand la réalité frappe trop fort et que le silence parle plus que les phrases.
J’ai pas les mots est un cri intérieur, un morceau sans masque, né de ce que la vie t’apprend sans jamais te prévenir.


Ce morceau s’adresse à ceux qui encaissent, qui tombent, qui se relèvent…
et qui parfois n’ont simplement plus les mots.

🎚️ Prod / Mix / Master : Taga

🎥 Vidéoclip : Monstroscity Production

🔔 Abonne-toi et soutiens le mouvement

👍 Like | 💬 Commente | 🔁 Partage


📲 Suis Boutot sur les réseaux :

Instagram 👉 @Boutot_officiel

 Facebook 👉 Boutot

TikTok 👉 @Boutot_officiel


#Boutot #JaiPasLesMots #RapQuebec #RapConscient #Taga #MonstroscityProduction


Lyrics: 

Refrain:
Ohhh, j’ai pas les mots
J’préfère passer ma vie dans l’jail
Que de voir ma femme regarder le ciel

Verse1
Les rues qui m’ont fait chantent encore mon histoire
J’vais pas t’mentir, j’ai souvent d’la misère à y croire
Tomber sur l’or, j’y garde espoir
J’ai la meilleure à mes côtés quand arrive le renfort
Mais j’ai changé de chemin, je vends pu de dope
J’ai tendu la main à un avenir sans la tôle
Viens pas m’casser les couilles, parce que ça va s’passer
J’appellerai jamais les cops, les problèmes j’aime ça les régler
Viens marcher sur mon terrain, tu vas voir j’connais pas la pitié
Mais pour ma femme, sur la place publique, j’peux m’faire lapider

Refrain
Ohhh, j’ai pas les mots
J’préfère passer ma vie dans l’jail
Que de voir ma femme regarder le ciel

Verse 2
On sait aujourd’hui c’qui pourrait m’arriver
Tous mes plans sont déjà tracés
Prêt pour le pire, mais j’attends toujours le bien
Tant que la noirceur se tient loin
Vie de viking, pis pas juste à moitié
Retraité à 32 ans, j’y avais jamais pensé
Donnez-moi le micro
Avec un putain de bon beat
J’vais faire chanter le quartier, le morceau sur repeat
Ouais
J’ai besoin d’toi dans ma vie
Si jamais je pars au ciel
Tu veilleras sur notre famille
Vous êtes devenus tout c’que j’ai
Et j’pourrais pas demander mieux
J’ai encore des douilles sur le cœur
Mais j’oublie tout ça dans tes yeux

Refrain
Ohhh, j’ai pas les mots
J’préfère passer ma vie dans l’jail
Que de voir ma femme regarder le ciel
